.TH KSMBDCTL "8" "" "ksmbd-tools @ksmbd_tools_version@" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
ksmbdctl \- unified management tool for ksmbd
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ksmbdctl
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBksmbdctl\fR is the unified management tool for \fBksmbd\fR, the in-kernel
CIFS/SMB3 server for Linux.
It replaces the individual \fBksmbd.addshare\fR, \fBksmbd.adduser\fR,
\fBksmbd.control\fR, and \fBksmbd.mountd\fR tools with a single command
using a subcommand-based interface.
.PP
\fBksmbdctl\fR manages user accounts, share configuration, server lifecycle,
debugging, and feature inspection.
It communicates with the \fBksmbd\fR kernel module via sysfs and generic
netlink, and manages configuration files
\fBksmbd.conf\fR(5) and \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5).
.SH "GLOBAL OPTIONS"
These options may be given before any command.
.TP
\fB\-C\fR, \fB\-\-config\fR=\fI\,CONF\/\fR
Use \fI\,CONF\/\fR as configuration file instead of \fB@sysconfdir@/ksmbd/ksmbd.conf\fR.
.TP
\fB\-P\fR, \fB\-\-pwddb\fR=\fI\,PWDDB\/\fR
Use \fI\,PWDDB\/\fR as user database instead of \fB@sysconfdir@/ksmbd/ksmbdpwd.db\fR.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Be verbose. Enables debug-level logging.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Output version information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Display help and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS "Server Lifecycle"
.TP
\fBksmbdctl start\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PORT\/\fR] [\fB\-n\fR[\fI\,WAY\/\fR]] [\fB\-j\fR]
Start the ksmbd daemon.
This is equivalent to running \fBksmbd.mountd\fR.
.RS
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-port\fR=\fI\,PORT\/\fR
Bind to \fI\,PORT\/\fR instead of TCP port \fB445\fR.
.TP
\fB\-n\fR, \fB\-\-nodetach\fR[=\fI\,WAY\/\fR]
Do not detach process from foreground.
If \fI\,WAY\/\fR is \fB1\fR, become process group leader (default).
If \fI\,WAY\/\fR is \fB0\fR, detach.
.TP
\fB\-j\fR, \fB\-\-json\-log\fR
Output logs as JSON objects.
.RE
.TP
\fBksmbdctl stop\fR
Shut down both the ksmbd daemon and the kernel server.
Sends \fBSIGTERM\fR to the daemon and writes to
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/kill_server\fR.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl reload\fR
Notify the ksmbd daemon to reload its configuration.
Sends \fBSIGHUP\fR to the daemon process.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl status\fR
Display server status: whether the ksmbd kernel module is loaded,
its version, whether the daemon is running with its PID, and
currently enabled debug components.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl features\fR
Display configured feature flags from \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5):
SMB2 leases, encryption, multichannel, durable handles, Fruit extensions,
signing mode, protocol version range, and worker thread count.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl version\fR
Output version information for both the userspace tools and
the loaded ksmbd kernel module.
.SS "User Management"
.PP
Users are stored in the \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5) database.
After any change, the daemon is automatically notified to reload.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user add\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PWD\/\fR] \fI\,USER\/\fR
Add \fI\,USER\/\fR to the user database.
If \fB\-p\fR is not given, the password is prompted interactively.
\fI\,USER\/\fR must be UTF-8, [1, 48) bytes, and cannot contain a colon.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user delete\fR \fI\,USER\/\fR
Delete \fI\,USER\/\fR from the user database.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user update\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PWD\/\fR] \fI\,USER\/\fR
Update the password for \fI\,USER\/\fR.
If \fB\-p\fR is not given, the password is prompted interactively.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user list\fR
List all users in the user database, one per line.
.SS "Share Management"
.PP
Shares are configured in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
After any change, the daemon is automatically notified to reload.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share add\fR [\fB\-o\fR \fI\,OPT\/\fR]... \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Add \fI\,SHARE\/\fR to the configuration file.
Share parameters can be given with \fB\-o\fR (e.g., \fB\-o "path = /srv/share"\fR).
This option can be given multiple times.
If no \fB\-o\fR options are given, parameters are prompted interactively.
\fI\,SHARE\/\fR must be UTF-8, [1, 64) bytes, and is case-insensitive.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share delete\fR \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Delete \fI\,SHARE\/\fR from the configuration file.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share update\fR [\fB\-o\fR \fI\,OPT\/\fR]... \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Update parameters for \fI\,SHARE\/\fR in the configuration file.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share list\fR
List all shares with their names and comments.
Requires the daemon to be running.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share show\fR \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Show all configuration parameters for \fI\,SHARE\/\fR.
.SS "Debug Controls"
.PP
Debug components control kernel-level debug printing via
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/debug\fR.
Requires the ksmbd module to be loaded.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug set\fR \fI\,COMPONENT\/\fR
Toggle debug printing for \fI\,COMPONENT\/\fR.
Valid components are \fBall\fR, \fBsmb\fR, \fBauth\fR, \fBvfs\fR,
\fBoplock\fR, \fBipc\fR, \fBconn\fR, and \fBrdma\fR.
Enabled components are shown enclosed in brackets (\fB[]\fR).
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug show\fR
Display currently enabled debug components.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug off\fR
Disable all debug output.
.SS "Configuration"
.TP
\fBksmbdctl config show\fR [\fI\,SECTION\/\fR]
Display the current configuration.
Without \fI\,SECTION\/\fR, shows all sections (global and all shares).
With \fI\,SECTION\/\fR, shows only that section
(e.g., \fBksmbdctl config show global\fR).
.TP
\fBksmbdctl config validate\fR
Parse and validate the configuration file and user database
without starting the daemon. Reports errors and exits.
.SH FILES
.TP
\fB@sysconfdir@/ksmbd/ksmbd.conf\fR
Server configuration file. See \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
.TP
\fB@sysconfdir@/ksmbd/ksmbdpwd.db\fR
User password database. See \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5).
.TP
\fB@runstatedir@/ksmbd.lock\fR
PID lock file for the daemon process.
.TP
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/kill_server\fR
Sysfs attribute to shut down the ksmbd kernel server.
.TP
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/debug\fR
Sysfs attribute to toggle kernel debug components.
.TP
\fB/sys/module/ksmbd/version\fR
Sysfs attribute showing the ksmbd kernel module version.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
The exit status is 0 on success and 1 on failure.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Start the server in the foreground:
\fBksmbdctl start \-\-nodetach\fR
.TP
Add a user:
\fBksmbdctl user add john\fR
.TP
Add a share non-interactively:
\fBksmbdctl share add myshare \-o "path = /srv/share" \-o "read only = no"\fR
.TP
Show server status:
\fBksmbdctl status\fR
.TP
Show feature configuration:
\fBksmbdctl features\fR
.TP
Enable SMB debug logging:
\fBksmbdctl debug set smb\fR
.TP
Validate configuration:
\fBksmbdctl config validate\fR
.TP
Show a specific share:
\fBksmbdctl share show myshare\fR
.TP
Reload configuration after manual edits:
\fBksmbdctl reload\fR
.TP
Shut down the server:
\fBksmbdctl stop\fR
.SH "BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY"
The legacy command names \fBksmbd.addshare\fR, \fBksmbd.adduser\fR,
\fBksmbd.control\fR, and \fBksmbd.mountd\fR are installed as symlinks
to \fBksmbdctl\fR and continue to work with their original syntax.
When invoked via a legacy name, the tool behaves identically to
the original command.
.SH SIGNALS
When running in daemon mode (\fBksmbdctl start\fR), the daemon responds to:
.TP
\fBSIGHUP\fR
Reload configuration files.
.TP
\fBSIGUSR1\fR
List current configuration to a named pipe.
.TP
\fBSIGTERM\fR, \fBSIGINT\fR, \fBSIGQUIT\fR
Shut down gracefully.
